            <div type="edition"><!-- transcription goes here -->
                <div type="textpart" subtype="ansa">
                    <ab>
                    <lb n="1"/><g type="hedera"/>
                    <lb n="2"/><persName>Auguria</persName>,
                    <lb n="3"/>anima
                    <lb n="4"/>dulcis et
                    <lb n="5"/>innocua,
                    <lb n="6"/>have.
                    <lb n="7"/><g type="hedera"></g>
                    </ab>
                </div>
            <div type="textpart" subtype="campus">
                <ab>
                    <lb n="1"/>Domui aeternae consecratae. <g type="hedera"/>
                    <lb n="2"/><persName><name type="gentilicium" key="Agileia">Agileiae</name> <name type="cognomen" key="Prima">Primae</name>, <expan><abbr>q</abbr><ex>uae</ex></expan> <expan><abbr>e</abbr><ex>t</ex></expan> <name type="cognomen" key="Auguria">Auguriae</name></persName>,
                    <lb n="3"/>uxori supra aetatem castissimae et
                    <lb n="4"/>pudicissimae et frugalissimae, quae innocenter
                    <lb n="5"/>maritum et domum eius amavit, omnia de se
                    <lb n="6"/>merenti fecit <persName><name type="praenomen" key="Quintus"><expan><abbr>Q</abbr><ex>uintus</ex></expan></name> <name type="gentilicium" key="Oppius">Oppius</name> <name type="cognomen" key="Secundus">Secundus</name></persName> maritus et sibi.
                    <lb n="7"/>Tempore quo sum genita natura mihi bis denos tribuit
                    <lb n="8"/>annos, quibus completis, septima deinde die resoluta
                    <lb n="9"/>legibus, otio sum perpetuo tradita; haec mihi vita fuit.
                    <lb n="10"/><persName><name type="gentilicium" key="Oppius"/>Oppi</persName>, ne metuas Lethen, nam stultum est tempore et om
                    <lb n="11" break="no"/>ni, dunc mortem metuas, amittere gaudia vitae.
                    <lb n="12"/>Mors etenim hominum natura non poena est;
                    <lb n="13"/>cui contigit nasci instat et mori igitur.
                    <lb n="14"/>Domine <persName><name type="gentilicium" key="Oppius"/>Oppi</persName> marite, ne doleas mei quod praecessi;
                    <lb n="15"/>sustineo in aeterno toro adventum tuum.
                    <lb n="16"/>Valete superi et cuncti cunctaeque valete.
                </ab>
            </div>
            <div type="textpart" subtype="ansa">
                <ab>
                    <lb n="1"/><g type="hedera"/>
                    <lb n="2"/><persName><name type="cognomen" key="Auguria">Auguria</name></persName>,
                    <lb n="3"/>innocua
                    <lb n="4"/>anima
                    <lb n="5"/>tua in
                    <lb n="6"/>bono.
                    <lb n="7"/><g type="hedera"/>
                </ab>
            </div>
            </div>
            <div type="translation">
                <p>Left Ansa: "Auguria, a sweet and gentle soul, farewell."</p>
                <p>Right Ansa: "Auguria, your gentle soul is in goodness."</p>
                <p>Campus: "For Agileia Prima, who is also (called) Auguria, consecrated to her eternal home, a wife most chaste beyond her age, and most modest and most temperate, who innocently loved her husband and his household; her husband, Quintus Oppius Secundus, made this for her, deserving everything about herself, and for himself. 'From the time when I was born Nature wore away from me twenty years, and after these were completed, finally on the seventh day, set free from all contracts, I was given over to eternal peace. This was my life. Oppius, do not fear Lethe, for it is foolish to forgo the joys of life at every instance, while you fear death. For indeed, death is the nature of humans, not a punishment; to whom it has befallen to be born, it follows accordingly to die as well. Lord Oppius, my husband, do not grieve for me because I have gone before you; in the eternal bed I hold off your arrival. Farewell, all you who dwell above, both men and women, farewell.'"</p>
            </div>
            <div type="commentary"><!-- notes go here -->
                <p>Left Ansa: "(hedera) Auguria ... have (hedera)"</p>
                <p>Body (lines 1-16: "domui aeternae
                    ... cunctaeque valete"): Line 1: written on the top border of the campus. Line
                    7: Change of speaker to the voice of the deceased. From lines 7-16, much greater
                    concentration of interpuncts (37 of 42). Line 9: "haec mihi vita fuit" scans as
                    half of a pentameter from an elegiac couplet. Lines 10-11: contain two full
                    hexamter lines ("ne metuas ... gaudia vitae"). Also, close parallel to Disticha
                    Catonis II.3. Lines 12-13: Line 12 is almost a hexameter. Line 13 contains echo
                    of Seneca, Epist. Mor. 99.8. Line 15: contains complete iambic senarius. Line
                    16: written on the bottom border of the campus, and almost a complete hexameter.</p>
                <p>Right Ansa: "(hedera) Auguria ... bono (hedera)"</p>
            </div>
            
